\sin{(3 \pi/5)} = \sin{(2 \pi/5)}
\sin{(3 \pi/5)} = 3 \sin{(\pi/5)} - 4 \sin^3{(\pi/5)} = 2 \sin{(\pi/5)} \cos{(\pi/5)}
2 \cos{(\pi/5)} = 3 - 4 \sin^2{(\pi/5)} = 4 \cos^2{(\pi/5)} - 1
y=\cos{(\pi/5)}
4 y^2-2 y-1=0 \implies y = \frac{1 + \sqrt{5}}{4}
